WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.910 --> 00:00:06.990
EVAN RAPOPORT: Hello everyone.

00:00:06.990 --> 00:00:08.550
Thank you for coming today.

00:00:08.550 --> 00:00:11.870
We are going to go over
the Views from Everywhere,

00:00:11.870 --> 00:00:15.660
how we're bringing the world's
largest photo library to you,

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:18.110
our developers, and to
those of you who have not

00:00:18.110 --> 00:00:20.360
stayed at the World Cup to
watch the last few minutes.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:23.870
So thank you for coming.

00:00:23.870 --> 00:00:24.840
I'm Evan Rapoport.

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:27.340
I'm a product manager on the
Street View in Google Maps

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:28.030
team.

00:00:28.030 --> 00:00:30.500
And this is Luc Vincent,
engineering director

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:33.130
for Street View and
trekker extraordinaire.

00:00:33.130 --> 00:00:36.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:36.700 --> 00:00:40.110
So I used to live in Hawaii,
and we had this great tradition

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:42.407
back here that I'm trying
to bring everywhere I go,

00:00:42.407 --> 00:00:44.740
especially when it's cold--
even though it's summer here

00:00:44.740 --> 00:00:45.980
in San Francisco.

00:00:45.980 --> 00:00:48.870
And that was where as a
speaker, I would say "Aloha,"

00:00:48.870 --> 00:00:50.650
and the entire room
would scream back

00:00:50.650 --> 00:00:52.150
"Aloha" with this
vigor that made

00:00:52.150 --> 00:00:53.990
you feel like it
was 80 degrees out.

00:00:53.990 --> 00:00:55.580
And kids did this really well.

00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:58.910
I used to teach in schools,
and everyone really enjoyed it,

00:00:58.910 --> 00:00:59.910
and it was a lot of fun.

00:00:59.910 --> 00:01:01.640
So we're going to
do it right now,

00:01:01.640 --> 00:01:04.056
and we're going to try to make
sure it feels a little warm

00:01:04.056 --> 00:01:05.160
here in San Francisco.

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:06.540
So, aloha!

00:01:06.540 --> 00:01:07.999
AUDIENCE: Aloha.

00:01:07.999 --> 00:01:09.040
EVAN RAPOPORT: Wonderful.

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:10.510
Ah, every time, I love it.

00:01:10.510 --> 00:01:11.260
Thank you so much.

00:01:11.260 --> 00:01:13.180
I really appreciate that.

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:15.454
So today this is what
we're going to go over.

00:01:15.454 --> 00:01:17.870
We're going to talk about how
over the last several years,

00:01:17.870 --> 00:01:20.910
we've been creating the world's
largest geolocated photo

00:01:20.910 --> 00:01:24.210
library through our efforts
in Street View in Google Maps.

00:01:24.210 --> 00:01:26.950
We're going to talk about
how you can add your imagery,

00:01:26.950 --> 00:01:29.617
just in case we've missed places
that you really care about.

00:01:29.617 --> 00:01:31.200
And then we're going
to talk about how

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:34.340
you can access all this
data, including your own,

00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:40.580
using our APIs and our viewers,
all at Google-scale serving.

00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:42.760
So why are we doing this?

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:44.845
I hate to be cheesy,
but it's kind of-- it's

00:01:44.845 --> 00:01:46.720
this beautiful world
out there, and we really

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.250
want to help you explore it.

00:01:48.250 --> 00:01:50.660
We really feel, at
the Google Maps team,

00:01:50.660 --> 00:01:52.500
that it's our opportunity,
and it's actually

00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:54.620
almost are our
mandate, to make sure

00:01:54.620 --> 00:01:57.700
that you have better real-world
experiences as you travel,

00:01:57.700 --> 00:01:59.730
as you make local decisions,
as you go somewhere

00:01:59.730 --> 00:02:00.660
on the weekend.

00:02:00.660 --> 00:02:03.620
And so we really want
to be the team that

00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:08.139
can help you have better
experiences in the real world.

00:02:08.139 --> 00:02:09.690
And we care so
much about photos--

00:02:09.690 --> 00:02:12.090
as you can tell by one of
the world's largest cameras

00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:16.010
sitting next to me-- that we
believe photos can inspire us.

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:19.280
We see photos like this and it
says, hey, I want to go there.

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:20.130
Where is that?

00:02:20.130 --> 00:02:23.020
Who hasn't seen that in
a post on social media?

00:02:23.020 --> 00:02:23.960
Where was that photo?

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:24.960
I want to go there.

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:26.940
This happens to be the
Sydney Harbour Bridge,

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:28.810
and I wouldn't suggest
hiking to the top

00:02:28.810 --> 00:02:30.130
during a lightning storm.

00:02:30.130 --> 00:02:33.870
But these are the kind of
things that inspire us.

00:02:33.870 --> 00:02:37.490
We see a photo like this and
we say, hey, to your family,

00:02:37.490 --> 00:02:38.640
let's go on a safari.

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:39.620
Let's travel the world.

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:42.300
Photos have this
opportunity to inspire us.

00:02:42.300 --> 00:02:45.320
And when they're on maps, it
tells us exactly where they are

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:46.470
and where we can go.

00:02:46.470 --> 00:02:49.200
And we're really
excited about this.

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:51.612
So without further ado,
I'd like to pass it over

00:02:51.612 --> 00:02:54.070
to Luc to talk about what we've
been doing with Street View

00:02:54.070 --> 00:02:56.500
to bring you imagery
all over the world.

00:02:56.500 --> 00:02:57.704
LUC VINCENT: Thanks, Evan.

00:02:57.704 --> 00:02:59.870
This is me in this picture
wearing this contraption,

00:02:59.870 --> 00:03:01.767
and this is me wearing
it right now live.

00:03:01.767 --> 00:03:02.850
I love wearing this thing.

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:05.130
We'll tell you more
about it later.

00:03:05.130 --> 00:03:07.400
What is our mission
in this team?

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:10.570
We would like to bring
imagery to our users,

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:12.350
our billions of
users, everywhere.

00:03:12.350 --> 00:03:15.900
And we want to collect it,
organize it, make it useful.

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:20.180
Our guiding principle really
is to be comprehensive,

00:03:20.180 --> 00:03:24.340
be everywhere, be useful,
obviously, and be accurate.

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:27.004
Imagery that we collect
around the world

00:03:27.004 --> 00:03:28.420
should be well
geolocated in order

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:29.990
to be useful in our products.

00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:31.756
So this is our mission.

00:03:31.756 --> 00:03:34.380
And I will tell you a little bit
about how we're going about it

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:36.650
and how we want make it
useful not just to our users

00:03:36.650 --> 00:03:39.940
but to developers worldwide.

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:43.370
So how do we go about
collecting this imagery?

00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:45.510
Well, as you probably
well know, we

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:48.020
have already satellite
imagery that we've

00:03:48.020 --> 00:03:51.240
had in our products
for about a decade.

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:54.080
And this imagery is,
in fact, very accurate.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:55.700
Even the clouds are accurate.

00:03:55.700 --> 00:04:00.790
If you use the new Google Maps,
the cloud cover is real-time.

00:04:00.790 --> 00:04:03.090
Zooming in further,
we have also collected

00:04:03.090 --> 00:04:05.740
and we are actively pursuing
collection of aerial imagery

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:06.450
around the world.

00:04:06.450 --> 00:04:11.180
And we use this oblique
imagery to create 3D cities, so

00:04:11.180 --> 00:04:15.020
3D models of urban
areas around the world.

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:18.410
We have hundreds of them now,
also making a map more useful.

00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:20.260
You can see here
one of the stadiums

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:23.400
we collected in Brazil
for the World Cup.

00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:28.260
We have all of them, I believe,
collected in 3D [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:31.830
And zooming even further, you
will see a familiar area here,

00:04:31.830 --> 00:04:32.540
the Bay Area.

00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:35.080
And in the new
Google Maps, we have

00:04:35.080 --> 00:04:37.230
made imagery much
more prominent.

00:04:37.230 --> 00:04:39.160
We have what we call
the runway, which

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:42.170
is this bar of pictures at the
bottom, which shows you imagery

00:04:42.170 --> 00:04:45.090
that's most relevant
to your current view.

00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:47.615
Imagery that's meant to be
useful and representative

00:04:47.615 --> 00:04:49.920
of what you're
interested in looking at.

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:51.790
We have imagery,
as you may notice,

00:04:51.790 --> 00:04:53.992
from-- we have
photos from users.

00:04:53.992 --> 00:04:55.450
Photo spheres--
and I will tell you

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:57.200
more about photo
spheres in a minute.

00:04:57.200 --> 00:04:58.870
We also have a lot
of street imagery.

00:04:58.870 --> 00:05:02.520
Street View remains the largest
corpus of geolocated photos

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:05.610
that we have in
our maps, and it's

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:09.350
something we've been working
on for almost a decade.

00:05:09.350 --> 00:05:11.750
So speaking of Street View,
let me tell you a little bit

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:15.030
about how we got started
with this crazy mission, what

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:17.760
we're doing about it
today, and then we'll

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:23.045
talk about our sort of expanding
community efforts in the Street

00:05:23.045 --> 00:05:25.160
View space.

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:28.680
So Street View started
actually over a decade ago.

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:31.820
It was an idea by
our CEO, Larry Page,

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:35.480
who felt really that
street-level imagery should

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:36.940
be useful to our users.

00:05:36.940 --> 00:05:39.280
And he really wanted
to make [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:41.050
accessible and useful.

00:05:41.050 --> 00:05:44.510
So he himself collected imagery
using a camcorder in the Bay

00:05:44.510 --> 00:05:47.620
Area and used the
footage he collected

00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:51.290
to bootstrap research, early on
at Stanford University and then

00:05:51.290 --> 00:05:52.410
at Google.

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:56.122
And in 2005, a group of
googlers, which I was part of,

00:05:56.122 --> 00:05:58.330
decided it was really time
to do something about this

00:05:58.330 --> 00:05:59.860
and to make this real.

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:03.290
So we developed a bunch of
computer visual algorithms

00:06:03.290 --> 00:06:05.590
and built a platform
to collect imagery.

00:06:05.590 --> 00:06:07.930
You see here in 2006,
we built these very

00:06:07.930 --> 00:06:11.320
large and crazy-looking vans
full of cameras and equipment,

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:14.590
which we sort of took around
the US-- in the Bay Area,

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:17.080
in particular-- and
collected imagery.

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:19.850
Enough imagery, and we were
able to process it enough,

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:21.350
to actually launch a product.

00:06:21.350 --> 00:06:24.060
We launched Street View
in 2007 in Google Maps

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:26.300
in first five cities.

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:30.890
And there was so much
interest and sort of traffic,

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:31.850
we couldn't believe it.

00:06:31.850 --> 00:06:33.433
So we thought we had
something useful,

00:06:33.433 --> 00:06:37.000
and so we worked hard to grow
this product and scale it.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:42.410
So you see here, over the
course of 2007 through 2008,

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:44.380
we actually expanded
our coverage in the US.

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:46.637
This is coverage
expanding rapidly here.

00:06:46.637 --> 00:06:48.720
And then we essentially
expanded the whole product

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:50.980
around the world,
and we're still

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:53.392
busy doing this right now.

00:06:53.392 --> 00:06:54.850
In the process of
doing this, we've

00:06:54.850 --> 00:06:57.370
hit just about any kind
of issue you may imagine.

00:06:57.370 --> 00:06:59.500
Unique problems
happened at scale.

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:01.440
For example, this one.

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:04.810
This is co collected imagery
in the Amazon, in Brazil,

00:07:04.810 --> 00:07:06.720
and frogs jumping on the camera.

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:08.380
How many of you
here, photographers,

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:10.540
have had frogs jump
on your camera?

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:11.880
Not very many, right?

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:12.674
So we've had that.

00:07:12.674 --> 00:07:14.590
We've had other encounters
with other animals,

00:07:14.590 --> 00:07:17.330
like donkeys in some parts
of the world, what have you.

00:07:17.330 --> 00:07:19.490
So anything can happen,
and has happened.

00:07:19.490 --> 00:07:21.320
So we've learned in the process.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:22.790
We've refined our processes.

00:07:22.790 --> 00:07:23.956
We've refined our algorithm.

00:07:23.956 --> 00:07:26.100
We've refined our cars,
our approach to it.

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:28.020
And you know, today
we're very proud to have

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:30.860
build a really global platform
for imagery collection.

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:31.875
This is our latest car.

00:07:31.875 --> 00:07:33.250
You've probably
seen them roaming

00:07:33.250 --> 00:07:35.230
the Bay Area and
wherever you live.

00:07:35.230 --> 00:07:40.320
We have them in lots of places,
and we're busy expanding.

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:43.660
In fact, we have realized,
not that long ago,

00:07:43.660 --> 00:07:46.250
that you couldn't just do this
only with cars, obviously.

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:47.890
The most beautiful
parts of the world

00:07:47.890 --> 00:07:49.250
are not accessible by cars.

00:07:49.250 --> 00:07:52.230
Imagine castles, parks, museums.

00:07:52.230 --> 00:07:53.950
So we've built a
variety of platforms

00:07:53.950 --> 00:07:55.690
derived from the
Street View car.

00:07:55.690 --> 00:07:58.790
You see we have
put it on a boat.

00:07:58.790 --> 00:08:01.740
We have designed
this tricycle that

00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:05.320
can be mounted on various
other parts, like on a train,

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:08.690
or it can be used by itself,
like here at Stonehenge.

00:08:08.690 --> 00:08:10.394
We have also a snowmobile.

00:08:10.394 --> 00:08:12.560
And we even have a partner
called the Catlin Seaview

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:17.730
Survey that's built a rig that
goes underwater to capture

00:08:17.730 --> 00:08:19.690
coral reefs, and
they use our platform

00:08:19.690 --> 00:08:22.670
to publish the imagery.

00:08:22.670 --> 00:08:25.800
We started launching
these special collections

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:28.440
of unique heritage
sites a few years ago,

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:31.145
and when we launched
Pompeii-- as you see here

00:08:31.145 --> 00:08:36.465
on the left in this picture--
the Italian heritage

00:08:36.465 --> 00:08:37.840
authorities actually
told us they

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:39.870
had noticed an increase
in foot traffic

00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:42.260
to Pompeii, 25% increase.

00:08:42.260 --> 00:08:46.530
And we've noticed similar
kind of increased traffic

00:08:46.530 --> 00:08:47.520
in some museums.

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:49.250
So we take this as
sort of evidence

00:08:49.250 --> 00:08:52.440
that our imagery is not
just for couch potatoes.

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:55.000
It's imagery that not just
lets you travel virtually,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.680
but inspires you to travel
physically and go to places

00:08:57.680 --> 00:08:58.760
and explore the world.

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:01.700
So we're very happy about this.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:03.830
So more recently, we've
built this Trekker, which

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:05.874
I'm currently wearing,
and we've taken it also

00:09:05.874 --> 00:09:07.540
to lots of places
where you can't really

00:09:07.540 --> 00:09:10.230
go other than by foot.

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:13.380
Here you see we've had a group
of googlers go to the Galapagos

00:09:13.380 --> 00:09:16.670
to capture a few of the
unique sights there.

00:09:16.670 --> 00:09:19.980
All this imagery is up in Maps.

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:26.030
And also was lucky enough to
go be part of the Grand Canyon

00:09:26.030 --> 00:09:29.500
rafting trip, where we took
these trekkers on two rafts

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:31.670
and captured the entire
length of the Grand Canyon.

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:33.420
And the imagery is now
live in Street View

00:09:33.420 --> 00:09:34.990
as well, on Google Maps.

00:09:34.990 --> 00:09:38.300
And this was really my
best business trip ever.

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:40.320
So it's really imagery
that not everybody

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:42.140
would be able to
capture themselves.

00:09:42.140 --> 00:09:45.290
So we like to bring it to people
who couldn't travel there.

00:09:45.290 --> 00:09:46.230
So where are we now?

00:09:46.230 --> 00:09:46.980
Here's our status.

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:48.640
We have driven--
we have launched

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:51.810
imagery in about 56
countries-- give and take,

00:09:51.810 --> 00:09:55.570
because some countries
don't necessarily count.

00:09:55.570 --> 00:09:59.580
We have over five
million miles live,

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:01.140
and that's about 20
times the descent

00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:03.840
from the Earth to the moon,
to give you a reference.

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:06.120
We have imagery on
all seven continents.

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:09.900
So we have been busy,
and we've learned a lot.

00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:12.307
But in fact, we have
even more than that,

00:10:12.307 --> 00:10:13.890
because we recently,
a few months ago,

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:17.680
launched what we call Street
View Time Machine, which

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:22.080
doesn't just let you explore a
place by moving geographically,

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:23.402
but lets you explore in time.

00:10:23.402 --> 00:10:25.110
So we added the fourth
dimension, really,

00:10:25.110 --> 00:10:30.230
to Street View and we help tell
the story of a place over time.

00:10:30.230 --> 00:10:32.820
If you go in Street View,
you will find lots of places

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:35.000
in Asia, where there's
frenetic construction.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.300
You will see the story of
construction over time.

00:10:37.300 --> 00:10:40.310
And you can explore at each sort
of time slice geographically,

00:10:40.310 --> 00:10:41.640
as well.

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:44.580
Sometimes, sadly, this is
also a story of destruction,

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:47.580
like here in Japan,
following the earthquake.

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:50.190
We have, actually,
imagery before and after.

00:10:50.190 --> 00:10:52.560
In fact, in many cases,
we found that Street View

00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:56.920
is the only photographic record
of places before disaster,

00:10:56.920 --> 00:10:59.770
which is amazing to us.

00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:01.400
However-- so we
have done all this.

00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:02.900
We have built this
amazing platform.

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:05.170
We have millions
of miles of imagery

00:11:05.170 --> 00:11:06.590
captured in lots of countries.

00:11:06.590 --> 00:11:08.500
But we still need help.

00:11:08.500 --> 00:11:09.000
Why?

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:09.625
Why is that so?

00:11:09.625 --> 00:11:12.580
Well, turns out if you really
wanted to capture imagery

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:15.160
everywhere, you would
need trillions of images.

