of these devices coming out

00:21:33.250 --> 00:21:35.840
on Kickstarter soon, or
that are on Kickstarter,

00:21:35.840 --> 00:21:38.050
that you may have seen, that
are launching this year.

00:21:38.050 --> 00:21:40.260
These are, again,
one-click 360 cameras

00:21:40.260 --> 00:21:42.270
that are going to create
Street View experiences

00:21:42.270 --> 00:21:44.740
and have used the Photo
Sphere metadata standard.

00:21:44.740 --> 00:21:47.024
So really exciting
year for all of us

00:21:47.024 --> 00:21:48.190
that are excited about 360s.

00:21:51.340 --> 00:21:53.570
We also had a great
collaboration with the Auto

00:21:53.570 --> 00:21:54.980
Awesome team in Google+.

00:21:54.980 --> 00:21:57.670
So if you don't know how to
add metadata into JPEGs--

00:21:57.670 --> 00:22:00.400
and let's face it, most of
us don't-- just upload these

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:01.640
images to Google+.

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:04.300
It recognizes that
it's a 2x1 panorama.

00:22:04.300 --> 00:22:07.160
It notices that the edges are
kind of matching each other.

00:22:07.160 --> 00:22:09.720
And it'll Auto Awesome and give
you back a copy of your image

00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:12.390
with the metadata in it,
that you can immediately put

00:22:12.390 --> 00:22:14.385
into Google Maps or
share on Google+.

00:22:17.260 --> 00:22:19.920
So let's talk a little bit
about how we can actually

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:23.599
get Photo Sphere
into your products.

00:22:23.599 --> 00:22:25.390
I want to dive into
some code really quick,

00:22:25.390 --> 00:22:27.140
so I'll talk about how
to actually publish

00:22:27.140 --> 00:22:28.049
to Maps in a minute.

00:22:28.049 --> 00:22:30.340
But let's talk about how to
actually just get these in.

00:22:30.340 --> 00:22:32.270
So iframe, not really
that much code.

00:22:32.270 --> 00:22:33.800
That's pretty simple.

00:22:33.800 --> 00:22:35.300
But I had to start
somewhere, right?

00:22:35.300 --> 00:22:37.250
So we have an embeddable viewer.

00:22:37.250 --> 00:22:39.680
If you go to Views, which
is a product I'll talk about

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:43.120
in a minute, you can simply copy
and paste this HTML snippet,

00:22:43.120 --> 00:22:45.640
put it right into your
apps or your products,

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:48.480
and you'll be able to view
photo spheres right there.

00:22:48.480 --> 00:22:50.700
It uses the same Street
View viewer that we have,

00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:52.510
so it's very robust.

00:22:52.510 --> 00:22:54.560
And we have no usage
limits for this.

00:22:54.560 --> 00:22:57.927
You can customize your
presentation of the image.

00:22:57.927 --> 00:22:59.510
You can tweak
parameters and all that.

00:22:59.510 --> 00:23:01.010
And it's a really
great and easy way

00:23:01.010 --> 00:23:05.497
to put photo spheres
into your websites.

00:23:05.497 --> 00:23:06.830
All right, a little bit of code.

00:23:06.830 --> 00:23:08.350
I wish I could make it
more complicated for you,

00:23:08.350 --> 00:23:09.630
but it's just not complicated.

00:23:09.630 --> 00:23:11.300
So it's very, very simple.

00:23:11.300 --> 00:23:14.180
If you're familiar with the
JavaScript API for Maps,

00:23:14.180 --> 00:23:16.370
there is a Street
View object in there.

00:23:16.370 --> 00:23:19.110
And usually you just set
the latitude and longitude

00:23:19.110 --> 00:23:21.770
as to where you want
the Street View panorama

00:23:21.770 --> 00:23:24.130
and we give you the nearest one.

00:23:24.130 --> 00:23:25.850
Well, in the case
of Photo Sphere,

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:28.340
you actually know the
exact image that you want.

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:30.620
And so there's a
property called pano,

00:23:30.620 --> 00:23:32.580
and you just tell
it the panorama ID

00:23:32.580 --> 00:23:35.250
that you're interested in--
which that iframe code that I

00:23:35.250 --> 00:23:37.250
just showed you about has
in it, so you can just

00:23:37.250 --> 00:23:38.990
copy and paste those out.

00:23:38.990 --> 00:23:41.870
And then we'll give you
back your photo sphere

00:23:41.870 --> 00:23:42.760
directly there.

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:44.980
It's really just that easy.

00:23:44.980 --> 00:23:46.270
There's not much more to say.

00:23:46.270 --> 00:23:48.270
You could build a gallery
with Photo Sphere,

00:23:48.270 --> 00:23:51.280
using this very, very easily.

00:23:51.280 --> 00:23:54.420
On Android, it's
again the same thing.

00:23:54.420 --> 00:23:56.140
Instead of specifying
a lat/long,

00:23:56.140 --> 00:23:59.080
you see I have a pano ID
field or a variable there.

00:23:59.080 --> 00:24:00.390
That's all you do.

00:24:00.390 --> 00:24:03.070
So specify that pano,
and we'll give you

00:24:03.070 --> 00:24:05.450
back that image instead of
the nearest Street View one.

00:24:05.450 --> 00:24:07.740
So very, very easy
for you to go,

00:24:07.740 --> 00:24:10.580
with Android, capturing
panoramas and then putting them

00:24:10.580 --> 00:24:12.920
directly back into
your Android app

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:17.190
without even having to go to a
desktop, if you don't want to.

00:24:17.190 --> 00:24:18.960
So I mentioned Views.

00:24:18.960 --> 00:24:21.750
Views is a community we created
to make this easier and easier

00:24:21.750 --> 00:24:24.690
for you to publish
panoramas to the web

00:24:24.690 --> 00:24:26.630
and create your Street
View experiences.

00:24:26.630 --> 00:24:29.980
So g.co/views, you
can go check that out.

00:24:29.980 --> 00:24:32.250
And this is a place
that brings together

00:24:32.250 --> 00:24:34.440
all of our great Street
View special collections

00:24:34.440 --> 00:24:39.260
and our Trekker collections,
but then also content from you.

00:24:39.260 --> 00:24:42.170
And then that content
gets shown on Google Maps.

00:24:42.170 --> 00:24:44.790
So it's really exciting for us
that when you look at a place

00:24:44.790 --> 00:24:47.170
here, like Half Dome, and
you see all the Street View

00:24:47.170 --> 00:24:51.680
paths winding their
way through Yosemite,

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:54.360
the leftmost image there,
the top-ranked image,

00:24:54.360 --> 00:24:57.630
actually happens to be from a
user, and it's a photo sphere.

00:24:57.630 --> 00:24:59.590
You'll see only one
Street View panorama

00:24:59.590 --> 00:25:02.710
on this but lots of
user-contributed content.

00:25:02.710 --> 00:25:05.600
We've made this content
really, really highly promoted

00:25:05.600 --> 00:25:07.364
because we think it's
the most interesting

00:25:07.364 --> 00:25:08.280
and the most relevant.

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:11.120
As Luc mentioned, the most
amazing things in the world

00:25:11.120 --> 00:25:12.780
usually aren't
seen from the road,

00:25:12.780 --> 00:25:15.560
and so you're able to
contribute these images.

00:25:15.560 --> 00:25:18.780
And how cool is it to
have the canonical view

00:25:18.780 --> 00:25:21.510
of Half Dome in Google
Maps be your image?

00:25:21.510 --> 00:25:24.360
I think that's just a
really neat experience,

00:25:24.360 --> 00:25:25.810
as a photographer, I guess.

00:25:25.810 --> 00:25:27.900
So back to Views.

00:25:27.900 --> 00:25:30.040
Views is a place that,
like Google Maps,

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:33.050
lets you browse over an area
that you're interested in

00:25:33.050 --> 00:25:35.320
and see all the
top-ranked imagery there.

