So we're looking
at Las Vegas here

00:25:37.420 --> 00:25:39.240
because I was recently
there for a talk.

00:25:39.240 --> 00:25:41.160
And all the images
on the right really

00:25:41.160 --> 00:25:43.190
just do match up
to the top spots

00:25:43.190 --> 00:25:44.980
that you would see
around Las Vegas.

00:25:44.980 --> 00:25:48.760
We also have a Top Photographers
list at the top of the site,

00:25:48.760 --> 00:25:50.750
so you can find
all the people who

00:25:50.750 --> 00:25:52.540
are really active contributors.

00:25:52.540 --> 00:25:55.090
And hey, if you're looking to
hire a photographer in a spot,

00:25:55.090 --> 00:25:59.480
this is a great way to find
some photographers, too.

00:25:59.480 --> 00:26:01.760
In Views, we also give
you a profile page,

00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:04.730
so sort of like a gallery
of your own imagery.

00:26:04.730 --> 00:26:06.200
And I really love this.

00:26:06.200 --> 00:26:08.620
This is mine, and it
just has all the images

00:26:08.620 --> 00:26:11.577
that I've been capturing
over the last year or so.

00:26:11.577 --> 00:26:13.410
I travel quite a bit
for work, and so you'll

00:26:13.410 --> 00:26:15.860
see a lot of red dots on my map.

00:26:15.860 --> 00:26:19.040
This is basically
showcasing my travels.

00:26:19.040 --> 00:26:20.750
And I use this
pretty regularly when

00:26:20.750 --> 00:26:22.800
friends ask me, like, what
should I do in Hawaii?

00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:24.510
Or what hike should
I do this weekend?

00:26:24.510 --> 00:26:27.477
I actually find the spots
there and then I send that off,

00:26:27.477 --> 00:26:29.560
and I say, great, these
are all the photos spheres

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:30.979
that I've taken in that spot.

00:26:30.979 --> 00:26:32.770
These would be my
recommendations of places

00:26:32.770 --> 00:26:33.790
that you should see.

00:26:33.790 --> 00:26:35.700
It's really helpful.

00:26:35.700 --> 00:26:37.320
I'm sure you could
find ways to think

00:26:37.320 --> 00:26:42.440
of how this would be relevant
to your business or your users.

00:26:42.440 --> 00:26:45.090
But we know that Photo Sphere
isn't fully Street View yet,

00:26:45.090 --> 00:26:45.590
right?

00:26:45.590 --> 00:26:47.580
It's about connected
experiences, not

00:26:47.580 --> 00:26:49.720
singular one-panorama images.

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:52.990
And so last year in December,
we announced a feature

00:26:52.990 --> 00:26:55.990
that lets you take a bunch
of dots and connect them,

00:26:55.990 --> 00:26:58.070
because it's really
just that easy.

00:26:58.070 --> 00:27:02.050
So you just dive into
this experience here

00:27:02.050 --> 00:27:03.770
and you connect the dots.

00:27:03.770 --> 00:27:04.979
That's what Street View is.

00:27:04.979 --> 00:27:06.020
It's connecting the dots.

00:27:06.020 --> 00:27:07.650
You fix the locations
a little bit.

00:27:07.650 --> 00:27:10.130
You rotate the images
if their compass heading

00:27:10.130 --> 00:27:11.330
wasn't quite on.

00:27:11.330 --> 00:27:13.930
And then you go ahead
and you publish that.

00:27:13.930 --> 00:27:18.890
It's basically from
your phone to this tool,

00:27:18.890 --> 00:27:20.982
and then right back
out to Street View.

00:27:20.982 --> 00:27:22.690
It's a very, very
quick and easy process.

00:27:22.690 --> 00:27:24.939
You could do the Moscone
Center by the end of the day,

00:27:24.939 --> 00:27:26.030
if you really wanted to.

00:27:26.030 --> 00:27:27.440
And if you do, come let me know.

00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:29.360
I'll get you a T-shirt.

00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:32.230
So everyone does things
for t-shirts, it seems.

00:27:32.230 --> 00:27:35.700
So we're really excited
about this, and as a result,

00:27:35.700 --> 00:27:39.070
we've seen some amazing things
coming in from our users.

00:27:39.070 --> 00:27:41.480
This is a great
user up in Montreal

00:27:41.480 --> 00:27:43.340
who went out in
the freezing cold

00:27:43.340 --> 00:27:46.720
and documented his local
park with 400 panoramas

00:27:46.720 --> 00:27:48.750
in the freezing cold--
as his hands were

00:27:48.750 --> 00:27:51.900
like, you know, barely kind
of able to open anymore--

00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:54.600
and documented the entire
park and published it

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:55.510
to Google Maps.

00:27:55.510 --> 00:27:57.810
And now this experience
is there for all of you

00:27:57.810 --> 00:28:00.540
to use in your apps,
to explore or to look.

00:28:00.540 --> 00:28:03.290
And it's just this
pride in the place

00:28:03.290 --> 00:28:06.860
that you live that really drove
him to go out and do that.

00:28:06.860 --> 00:28:10.290
So I challenge you to go
out there and find places

00:28:10.290 --> 00:28:14.240
that you care about and
document those, too.

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:16.921
So we've spoken a lot
about how to do things,

00:28:16.921 --> 00:28:19.420
and we've talked a lot about
why you would do it-- you know,

00:28:19.420 --> 00:28:21.740
to inspire people to
travel and to help

00:28:21.740 --> 00:28:22.960
them make good decisions.

00:28:22.960 --> 00:28:25.460
So I also want to talk a little
bit strategically about some

00:28:25.460 --> 00:28:30.660
of the benefits that this has
for you and for your clients.

00:28:30.660 --> 00:28:32.779
So who puts photos
on social media?

00:28:32.779 --> 00:28:34.070
I don't even need to see hands.

00:28:34.070 --> 00:28:35.460
That's probably everybody.

00:28:35.460 --> 00:28:38.391
So we all put photos
up there, and then we

00:28:38.391 --> 00:28:40.640
know that everyone's going
to see it right now, right?

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:42.800
You publish this photo,
you get lots of engagement

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:45.350
immediately over a few
minutes, maybe a few hours--

00:28:45.350 --> 00:28:48.160
maybe even a few days,
if you're really popular.

00:28:48.160 --> 00:28:50.120
When you put photos
on Google Maps,

00:28:50.120 --> 00:28:52.026
people are not going
to see it immediately

00:28:52.026 --> 00:28:53.400
at this really,
really high rate.

00:28:53.400 --> 00:28:54.380
What they're in
fact going to see

00:28:54.380 --> 00:28:56.550
is when it's relevant
to them-- when they're

00:28:56.550 --> 00:28:59.010
planning trips, when they're
thinking about travel, when

00:28:59.010 --> 00:29:00.860
they're dreaming of
their next vacation.

00:29:00.860 --> 00:29:02.570
And so if that's
important to you,

00:29:02.570 --> 00:29:05.220
this is exactly what you
need to be thinking about.

00:29:05.220 --> 00:29:08.410
This is where people
go to plan these trips.

00:29:08.410 --> 00:29:10.720
They probably don't go look
at a social media channel

00:29:10.720 --> 00:29:12.220
to think about a vacation.

00:29:12.220 --> 00:29:14.810
And even the most beautiful
photo you see right there

00:29:14.810 --> 00:29:18.660
might not be actually
the right time for them

00:29:18.660 --> 00:29:20.740
to be thinking about a trip.

00:29:20.740 --> 00:29:22.650
And so I like to
think of it this way.

00:29:22.650 --> 00:29:24.920
This is a graph--
there's no numbers on it,

00:29:24.920 --> 00:29:27.624
it's a concept-- of
total views over time,

00:29:27.624 --> 00:29:29.790
of thinking about how many
views your photo is going

00:29:29.790 --> 00:29:32.240
to get over time and
what kind of engagement

00:29:32.240 --> 00:29:33.390
you're going to expect.

00:29:33.390 --> 00:29:36.030
In social media, again, you
get these great spikes and this

00:29:36.030 --> 00:29:38.880
is a really amazing way to get
your message out right now.

00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:39.790
Definitely, do that.

00:29:39.790 --> 00:29:41.240
It's really, really valuable.

00:29:41.240 --> 00:29:43.890
But what we've seen, and as
the data starts to show--

00:29:43.890 --> 00:29:47.550
and I'll show you some data
in a minute-- over time

00:29:47.550 --> 00:29:50.360
you're going to get far more
engagement for relevant places

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:52.280
and interesting places
when you publish

00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:54.630
content in a
maps-based environment.

00:29:54.630 --> 00:29:57.220
Because again, it's
constantly relevant to people

00:29:57.220 --> 00:29:59.510
over and over and over
again throughout time,

00:29:59.510 --> 00:30:01.170
as long as that
place continues to be

00:30:01.170 --> 00:30:03.190
a place that people
are looking at.

00:30:03.190 --> 00:30:05.620
Again, Google Maps
has a billion users.

00:30:05.620 --> 00:30:09.590
A billion users are going
to see these places.

00:30:09.590 --> 00:30:12.240
And so I'm suspecting this
is a skeptical audience that

